orne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:18:21','2014-02-26 04:18:21','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(149,1,'2014-02-26 04:18:56','2014-02-26 04:18:56','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home.  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop their orphanage.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now,the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.\r\n\r\nFor practical reasons they have evolved gradually into their current set up in which they only have girls under their care.  The boys they previously had have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is also some turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school for slum children at Sahar. Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:18:56','2014-02-26 04:18:56','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(151,1,'2014-02-26 04:36:37','2014-02-26 04:36:37','There are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease or violent crime or self neglect or are in prison.\r\n\r\nSome of the kids are not \"orphans\" but have been brought by a parent or family member because they are physically or financially unable to care for them.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and this individual will eventually accept the child back.   But while they are there, the HMBT Sisters care for them completely.\r\n\r\nOn a typical day they will arise at 5:30-6:00 am.  After eating breakfast they will get dressed and ready for school which  goes till the early afternoon.   At Sahar the school is in the same building;  at Merces-Giriz the kids take a bus or walk to nearby independent schools.   In the mid-afternoon there is additonal tutoring by a paid teacher at Sahar and by volunteer local college students at Merces-Giriz .  In the late afternoon the kids all do chores, have play time,  take baths, eat dinner and have prayer time.  They typically go to bed around 9 pm.    On Sundays, there is extra time for watching T.V.,  having a party, music, dance,  and also visits by family members or persons from the community.\r\n\r\nOn this page you will find some profiles typical of the orphans.','Orphans','','publish','open','closed','','orphans','','','2014-02-26 15:01:18','2014-02-26 15:01:18','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=151',2,'page','',0),(152,1,'2014-02-26 04:36:37','2014-02-26 04:36:37','','Orphans','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:36:37','2014-02-26 04:36:37','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/151-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(171,1,'2014-02-26 05:02:12','2014-02-26 05:02:12','On this page you will see a brief biographical sketch of key people of the HMBT','Sister Bios','','inherit','open','open','','7-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 05:02:12','2014-02-26 05:02:12','',7,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/7-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(153,1,'2014-02-26 04:38:54','2014-02-26 04:38:54','<strong>This is the Stories page!</strong>\r\n\r\nLorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Curabitur nec semper sapien, eget varius ante. Quisque eleifend id turpis ut tempor. Fusce in velit nulla. Cum sociis natoque penatibus et magnis dis parturient montes, nascetur ridiculus mus. In nec mauris fringilla, sodales enim sed, auctor ligula. Ut pretium neque euismod mi imperdiet pharetra. Nulla arcu erat, consectetur quis ornare in, varius nec turpis. Praesent ligula nulla, placerat eleifend tincidunt id, vulputate in nunc. Curabitur id risus vehicula, varius eros sed, tempor mauris. Nunc luctus faucibus justo a eleifend. Maecenas sit amet turpis semper, molestie libero eget, egestas urna. Pellentesque quis luctus urna. Mauris elementum elit at congue viverra. Aenean tempus ipsum non arcu tincidunt consectetur.','Sister Bios','','inherit','open','open','','7-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:38:54','2014-02-26 04:38:54','',7,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/7-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(172,1,'2014-02-26 05:02:49','2014-02-26 05:02:49','','Diary of a Visit','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 05:02:49','2014-02-26 05:02:49','',9,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/9-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(154,1,'2014-02-26 04:43:03','2014-02-26 04:43:03','Preeti was born in April 2000.  She has been living at Merces Orphanage since the age of 5.   Her dad died of tuberculosis just before.   Her mother brought her to the orphange because she couldn\'t take care of her.  In 2013 her mother also died of tuberculosis.   Preeti has been treated and cured.\r\n\r\nPreeti is first in her class of 47 students at nearby St. Thomas High School where she takes Geography,  English,  History, Science, Math, Drawing and a computer class.  Her favorite subject is English.  She hopes to become a teacher someday.  She is very happy to be living at this orphanage and is greatful to the sisters for looking after her.','Preeti Kutade','','publish','open','closed','','preeti-kutade','','','2014-02-26 14:21:20','2014-02-26 14:21:20','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=154',0,'page','',0),(155,1,'2014-02-26 04:43:03','2014-02-26 04:43:03','','Preeti Kutade','','inherit','open','open','','154-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:43:03','2014-02-26 04:43:03','',154,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/154-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(156,1,'2014-02-26 04:44:05','2014-02-26 04:44:05','Ruby was born in June 1999.   Both of her parents passed away of unknown causes.  She was living with her sister but upon her sister\'s marriage she was brought to the Merces Orphanage about a year ago.\r\n\r\nRuby\'s favorite subjects in school are Speech (in which she enters competitions) and Singing (for which she has won awards).  She hopes someday to be a doctor because it is \"a respectable career\".   She really values all the people caring for her at the orphanage and feels a sense of community.  She said she would rather stay at the orphanage than to go back to her previous life.','Ruby Kureshi','','publish','open','open','','ruby-kureshi','','','2014-02-26 14:27:55','2014-02-26 14:27:55','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=156',1,'page','',0),(157,1,'2014-02-26 04:44:05','2014-02-26 04:44:05','','Ruby Kureshi','','inherit','open','open','','156-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:44:05','2014-02-26 04:44:05','',156,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/156-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(158,1,'2014-02-26 04:44:41','2014-02-26 04:44:41','Supriya is currently in 6th standard and has lived at the Merces Orphanage since 2007.   When both her parents died of tuberculosis she was brought to the orphanage by her grandmother who  had to go to work and had no means to support her.   She is expected to return to her grandmother after 10th grade but she is not sure she wants to go back.   She has one brother who is 14 years old who lives in another orphanage and visits on Sundays.\r\n\r\nSupriya attends St. Anthony\'s Convent School where she is average in her class of 80 kids.  She hopes to be an aritist someday.','Supriya Naka','','publish','open','open','','supriya-naka','','','2014-02-26 14:36:19','2014-02-26 14:36:19','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=158',2,'page','',0),(159,1,'2014-02-26 04:44:41','2014-02-26 04:44:41','','Supriya Naka','','inherit','open','open','','158-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:44:41','2014-02-26 04:44:41','',158,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/158-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(160,1,'2014-02-26 04:45:14','2014-02-26 04:45:14','Arti was born in September 1998.  Her father divorced her mother and ran away.  Her mother works as a live-in-maid in someone\'s house and is unable to have Arti with her but visits her on Sundays.\r\n\r\nShe is currently in the 8th standard and has lived at Merces Orphanage since 2009.  She hopes someday to become a police officer because she \"wants to enforce justice\".','Arti Gaikwade','','publish','open','open','','arti-gaikwade','','','2014-02-26 14:39:30','2014-02-26 14:39:30','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=160',3,'page','',0),(161,1,'2014-02-26 04:45:14','2014-02-26 04:45:14','','Arti Gaikwade','','inherit','open','open','','160-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:45:14','2014-02-26 04:45:14','',160,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/160-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(162,1,'2014-02-26 04:46:30','2014-02-26 04:46:30','Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','publish','open','open','','tulsi-gauri-shetty','','','2014-02-26 14:49:15','2014-02-26 14:49:15','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=162',4,'page','',0),(163,1,'2014-02-26 04:46:30','2014-02-26 04:46:30','','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:46:30','2014-02-26 04:46:30','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(164,1,'2014-02-26 04:47:01','2014-02-26 04:47:01','Sneha was born September 2003.   She is currently healthy.  She has been living at the Sahar Orphanage since the age of 3 when she was brought there by her grandmother who still visits.\r\n\r\nHer father had burned her mother to death over a property dispute and spent some time in jail.  His brother bought for him his way out of jail within the corrupt system in India.  He is forbidden from seeing Sneha.  Her brother Sopnil is 2 years older.  He was living at the Merces Orphange but is currently at another orphanage.\r\n\r\nShe attends 3rd standard at the Sahar Orphanage School and is maintaining an average academic performance in her class of 50 students.','Sneha Borde','','publish','open','open','','sneha-borde','','','2014-02-26 14:58:20','2014-02-26 14:58:20','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=164',5,'page','',0),(165,1,'2014-02-26 04:47:01','2014-02-26 04:47:01','','Sneha Borde','','inherit','open','open','','164-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:47:01','2014-02-26 04:47:01','',164,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/164-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(166,1,'2014-02-26 14:06:26','2014-02-26 14:06:26','There are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease or violent crime or self neglect or are in prison.\n\nSome of the kids are not \"orphans\" but have been brought by a parent or family member because they are physically or financially unable to care for them.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and this individual will eventually accept the child back.   But while they are there, the HMBT Sisters care for them completely.\n\nOn a typical day they will arise at 5:30-6:00 am.  After eating breakfast they will get dressed and ready for school which typically goes till the early afternoon.   At Sahar the school is in the same building;  at Merces-Giriz the kids walk to nearby independent schools.   In the mid-afternoon there is additonal tutoring by a paid teacher at  Sahar and by volunteer local college students at Merces-Giriz .  In the late afternoon the kids all do chores, have play time,  take baths, eat dinner and have prayer time.  They typically go to bed around 9 pm.    On Sundays, there is extra time for watching T.V.,  having a party, music, dance and also visits by\n\nOn this page you will find the profiles of some typical orphans.','Orphans','','inherit','open','open','','151-autosave-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:06:26','2014-02-26 14:06:26','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/151-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(167,1,'2014-02-26 04:55:11','2014-02-26 04:55:11','There are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease or violent crime or self neglect or are in prison.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and will eventually accept them back.   On this page you will find the profiles of some typical orphans.','Orphans','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:55:11','2014-02-26 04:55:11','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/151-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(168,1,'2014-02-26 04:58:15','2014-02-26 04:58:15','This is the projects page','Current Needs','','inherit','open','open','','34-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 04:58:15','2014-02-26 04:58:15','',34,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/34-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(169,1,'2014-02-26 05:00:40','2014-02-26 05:00:40','*  The main orphanage house at Merces has a leaking roof over the room in which  the kids have shelves to put their school bags and books.  The sisters would like to remedy this by constructing a covered terrace above this room which will also give a space to hang up all the laundry to dry.  Currently the clothes are washed by hand as part of the chores of the orphans.   There is no covered place to hang laundry for drying - so there is no way to dry clothes when it rains.    The estimated cost for this project is: _________\r\n\r\nXXXX ATTACH PICTURES OF THE LEAKING ROOF XXXX\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n* The electrical wiring in the main orphanage house at Merces needs to be replaced.  Currently there are exposed wires and the wires are in dis-repair.   The estimated cost for this project is:_________\r\n\r\nXXXXX  ATTACH PICTURES OF EXPOSED WIRING XXXXX\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Current Needs','','publish','open','open','','current-needs','','','2014-03-01 17:27:29','2014-03-01 17:27:29','',11,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=169',0,'page','',0),(170,1,'2014-02-26 05:00:40','2014-02-26 05:00:40','','Current Needs','','inherit','open','open','','169-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 05:00:40','2014-02-26 05:00:40','',169,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/169-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(176,1,'2014-02-26 05:10:59','2014-02-26 05:10:59','This is a log of a visit to the HMBT orphanages written by a 13 year old girl and her father.','Diary of a Visit','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 05:10:59','2014-02-26 05:10:59','',9,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/9-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(177,1,'2014-02-26 12:55:15','2014-02-26 12:55:15','There are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease or violent crime or self neglect or are in prison.\r\n\r\nSome of the kids are not \"orphans\" but have been brought by a parent or family member because they are physically or financially unable to care for them.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and this individual will eventually accept the child back.   But while they are there, the HMBT Sisters care for them completely.\r\n\r\nOn this page you will find the profiles of some typical orphans.','Orphans','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 12:55:15','2014-02-26 12:55:15','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/151-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(178,1,'2014-02-26 13:01:15','2014-02-26 13:01:15','<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A safe and nurturing place</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Flum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in greater Mumbai, India:  Sahar (Church Pakdi) Slum and Merces-Giriz</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT)</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In existence since 1990</p>\n</li>\n</ul>','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-autosave-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:01:15','2014-02-26 13:01:15','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(180,1,'2014-02-26 13:01:52','2014-02-26 13:01:52','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A safe and nurturing place</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in greater Mumbai, India:  Sahar (Church Pakdi) Slum and Merces-Giriz</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT) since 1989</li>\r\n</ul>','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:01:52','2014-02-26 13:01:52','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(181,1,'2014-02-26 13:02:52','2014-02-26 13:02:52','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A safe and nurturing place</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in Mumbai, India:   Sahar  Slum  and   Merces-Giriz</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT) since 1989</li>\r\n</ul>','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:02:52','2014-02-26 13:02:52','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(182,1,'2014-02-26 13:03:05','2014-02-26 13:03:05','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A safe and nurturing place</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in Mumbai, India:   Sahar Slum  and   Merces-Giriz</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT) since 1989</li>\r\n</ul>','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:03:05','2014-02-26 13:03:05','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(183,1,'2014-02-26 13:03:22','2014-02-26 13:03:22','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A safe and nurturing place</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in Mumbai, India:   Sahar Slum  and  Merces-Giriz</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT) since 1989</li>\r\n</ul>','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:03:22','2014-02-26 13:03:22','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(184,1,'2014-02-26 13:12:34','2014-02-26 13:12:34','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now,the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 to now about 40 nuns (about 10 of these involved with the orphanages).\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually, for practical reasons,  into their current set up in which they are a girls only orphanages.  The boys  previously residing there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school for slum children at Sahar. Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:12:34','2014-02-26 13:12:34','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(185,1,'2014-02-26 13:20:11','2014-02-26 13:20:11','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 to now about 40 nuns (about 10 of these involved with the orphanages).\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually, for practical reasons,  into their current set up in which they are a girls only orphanages.  The boys  previously residing there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school for slum children at Sahar. Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:20:11','2014-02-26 13:20:11','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(186,1,'2014-02-26 13:21:00','2014-02-26 13:21:00','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 to now about 40 nuns (about 10 of these involved with the orphanages).\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually, for practical reasons,  into their current set up in which they are  girls only orphanages.  The boys  previously residing there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school for slum children at Sahar. Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:21:00','2014-02-26 13:21:00','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(187,1,'2014-02-26 13:23:51','2014-02-26 13:23:51','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 to now about 40 nuns (about 10 of these involved with the orphanages).\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually, for practical reasons,  into their current set up in which they are  girls only orphanages.  The boys  previously residing there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school for slum children at Sahar. Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:23:51','2014-02-26 13:23:51','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(188,1,'2014-02-26 13:55:59','2014-02-26 13:55:59','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 to now about 40 nuns (about 10 of these involved with the orphanages).\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually, for practical reasons,  into their current set up in which they are  girls only orphanages.  The boys  previously residing there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even the non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:55:59','2014-02-26 13:55:59','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(189,1,'2014-02-26 13:57:27','2014-02-26 13:57:27','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A safe and nurturing place</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in Mumbai, India:   Sahar Slum Orphanage &amp; School  and  Merces-Giriz Orphanages</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT) since 1989</li>\r\n</ul>','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 13:57:27','2014-02-26 13:57:27','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(190,1,'2014-02-26 14:07:05','2014-02-26 14:07:05','There are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease or violent crime or self neglect or are in prison.\r\n\r\nSome of the kids are not \"orphans\" but have been brought by a parent or family member because they are physically or financially unable to care for them.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and this individual will eventually accept the child back.   But while they are there, the HMBT Sisters care for them completely.\r\n\r\nOn a typical day they will arise at 5:30-6:00 am.  After eating breakfast they will get dressed and ready for school which typically goes till the early afternoon.   At Sahar the school is in the same building;  at Merces-Giriz the kids walk to nearby independent schools.   In the mid-afternoon there is additonal tutoring by a paid teacher at  Sahar and by volunteer local college students at Merces-Giriz .  In the late afternoon the kids all do chores, have play time,  take baths, eat dinner and have prayer time.  They typically go to bed around 9 pm.    On Sundays, there is extra time for watching T.V.,  having a party, music, dance and also visits by family members or persons from the community.\r\n\r\nOn this page you will find the profiles of some typical orphans.','Orphans','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:07:05','2014-02-26 14:07:05','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com